05223nam a22009975i 9780228009993DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280099937 a10.1515/97802280099932doi  a(DE-B1597)657106  a(OCoLC)1273200968  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aS557.C32bO66 2022 7aSOC0260202bisacsh04a630.74/7132231 aNurse, Jodey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultivating Community :bWomen and Agricultural Fairs in Ontario /cJodey Nurse. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b28 photos, 16 tables, 3 diagrams  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Rural, Wildland, and Resource Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGetting on Board -- tFeeding the Family -- tCultivating Beauty -- tProviding Comfort, Refinement, and Respectability -- tGetting Outside the Inside Show -- tFrom Church Booths to Baby Shows -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor close to two hundred years, families and individuals across Ontario have travelled down country roads and gathered to enjoy seasonal agricultural fairs. Though some features of township and county fairs have endured for generations, these community events have also undergone significant transformations since 1850, especially in terms of women’s participation.Cultivating Community tells the story of how women’s involvement became critical to agricultural fairs’ growth and prosperity. By examining women’s diverse roles as agricultural society members, fair exhibitors, performers, volunteers, and fairgoers, Jodey Nurse shows that women used fairs’ manifold nature to present different versions of rural womanhood. Although traditional domestic skills and handicrafts, such as baking, needlework, and flower arrangement, remained the domain of women throughout this period, women steadily enlarged their sphere of influence on the fairgrounds. By the mid-twentieth century they had staked out a place in venues previously closed to them, including the livestock show ring, the athletic field, and the boardroom.Through a wealth of fascinating stories and colourful detail, Cultivating Communities adds a new dimension to the social and cultural history of rural women, placing their activities at the centre of the agricultural fair.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural exhibitionsxSocial aspectszOntarioxHistory. 0aAgricultural exhibitionsxSocial aspectszOntario. 0aAgricultural exhibitionszOntarioxHistory. 0aAgricultural exhibitionszOntario. 0aWomen in agriculturezOntarioxHistory. 0aWomen in agriculturezOntario. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Rural.2bisacsh  a4-H.  aOAAS.  aOntario association.  aagricultural societies.  aart.  abaking.  abiography.  acommunity service.  acompetition.  acooperation.  adomesticity.  aentertainment.  aexhibitions.  afall fairs.  afancywork.  afarming.  afemininity.  afeminism.  afood.  agardening.  ahousehold economy.  aimprovement.  aindustry.  aleadership.  alesiure.  alivestock.  amanufactures.  amaterial culture.  arecreation.  arefinement.  arespectability.  arural women.  avoluntary organizations.  awomanhood.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800999340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978022